The root issue (as I understand it) is: casting a pointer (which in ISO C is a pointer to an object) to a function(-pointer) is not defined. *But* dlsym does it and on every platform where dlsym exists, the cast is defined and works, on all platforms where this does not work (are there any?), there is also no way OpenGL will work, since it does the loading through void* as well. 
So we don't need to care about the cast itself, only about the warning beeing 'annoying'.

I still think the "correct" solution is simply to drop `-pedantic` for glad. But nothing speaks against making it easier for the end user. So as long as the changes make it easier and don't break existing code I am fine with them.

So the cast from `glfwGetProcAddress` to `GLADloadproc` still needs to succeed (same for SDL), `gladLoadGLLoader((GLADloadproc) glfwGetProcAddress)`, I am pretty sure doing your initial change:
```c
typedef void (*GLADvoidfn)(void);
typedef GLADvoidfn (*GLADloadproc)(const char *name);
```
Can't 100% confirm if that works with `-ansi -Wall`. Your change would basically move the issue to the cast from glad to passing the loader to glad (user code). 

Basically how it looks:

```c
typedef void (*GLADvoidfn)(void);
typedef GLADvoidfn (*GLADloadproc)(const char *name);
 
void* some_loader_func(const char *name) {
	return (void*)0;
}
 
void the_glad_loader(GLADloadproc load) {} 
 
int main(void) {
	the_glad_loader((GLADloadproc) some_loader_func);
	return 0;
}
```

The fix looks good to me, the only issue I can think of right now is with the builtin loader, but that can be 'fixed' by changing the signature to return the function pointer type -> good old `-pedantic` issue, but I guess that's fine.

nice idea :) but memcpy would result in the same suspected strict aliasing breakage, right?
The union trick would do for my current project but I suspect many users want C++ support.

The question is, does this violate strict aliasing?:
```
typedef void (*GLADvoidfn)(void);
...
    GLADvoidfn f;
    *(void **)(&f) = SDL_GL_GetProcAddress(name);
    return f;
...
```
I'm guessing that f could be returned as garbage if the compiler were to decide that f will not be affected by the assignment since the pointer to f has a different type than the pointer being dereferenced and written to?

