> > My recommendation would be to try and make it a simple list of Channel objects (not some user-defined type). That way clients get the familiar syntax of a list: I.e. chans = session.channels[0:2] +session.channels[5:10]. And can easily iterate over it.

> I imagine the most common case is to set all channels the same. A list of channel objects is more cumbersome for that

I agree. The channels object would be better off as an object with an overridden __setitem__ and __iter__ dunders rather than a simple list. This would allow for setting all the channels at the same time, while providing the familiar syntax of a list. Additionally it would allow for two types of channel selection modes:

For a session that contains all even channels on a 24 channel device, the following calls would be the same:
```python
session.channels["0,2,4,6,8"]
session.channels[0:4]
```

This is also the approach used in the .NET API:
