@legokangpalla: So many things are being done wrong at wo many levels, it's difficult to know where to begin.

First, keep in mind that _makeotf_ needs information to build the 'cmap' table. For CID-keyed fonts, this means supplying a UTF-32 CMap resource, which explicitly maps UTF-32 code points to CIDs. For name-keyed fonts, the glyphs either need to be named according to standard conventions, such as "space" for the space (U+0020) character, or named according to their Unicode code point, such as "uni0020" for the space character.

When you executed the `tx -t1 -decid -usefd 0 -g /0,/123 NanumBrush.otf temp.ps` command, the resulting font should include glyphs named ".notdef" and "cid123." The glyph named "cid123" is meaningless to _makeotf_ without special treatment. You would need to use either _mergeFonts_ or _rotateFont_ to rename the glyph. In fact, both of those tools are able to subset fonts and rename glyphs. The former can subset like _tx_, but you first need to use _tx_ to convert from CID-keyed to name-keyed, then run _mergeFonts_ with a mapping file to rename the glyphs. The latter requires a mapping file that can both subset the font and rename its glyphs. It's a bit more complicated than that, so I encourage you to read [Adobe Tech Note 5900](https://wwwimages2.adobe.com/content/dam/Adobe/en/devnet/font/pdfs/5900.RFMFAH_Tutorial.pdf).

About running `makeotf -f temp.ps -o NanumBrushSubset.otf -ch KSCpc-EUC-H`, there seems to be two problems. One is that it seems that you need to supply a minimal "features" file. The following contents should suffice:

```
table head {
  FontRevision 1.000;
} head;
```

The other is that the "-ch" command-line option is for specifying a Unicode CMap resource. "KSCpc-EUC-H" is not such a beast. That would be an appropriate CMap resource as the augment for the "-cm" command-line option. Try using "UniKS-UTF32-H" instead.

BTW, the glyph for [Adobe-Korea1-2](https://wwwimages2.adobe.com/content/dam/Adobe/en/devnet/font/pdfs/5093.Adobe-Korea1-2.pdf) CID+123 should look like U+300B 》.

